based exploitation. Through a thoughtful analysis of the rise of the Tea Party and the largely successful “blackening” of President Obama, Dawson ultimately argues that black politics remains weak—and that achieving the dream of racial and economic equality will require the sort of coalition-building and reaching across racial divides that have always marked successful political movements. Polemical but astute, passionate but pragmatic, Not in Our Lifetimes forces us to rethink easy assumptions about racial progress—and begin the hard work of creating real, lasting change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxAttitudes. 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitics and government. 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005xSocial aspects. 0aUnited States - Race relations - Public opinion. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  asocial policy, civil rights, personal freedoms, liberties, discrimination, racism, race relations, political science, postracial america, black movements, president obama, hurricane katrina, economic equality, politics, united states, justice, government, african americans, attitudes, multiracial alliances, public opinion, progress.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226138657423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226138657/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles